R-T-O and R-P-O, the only two numbers that matter.

Every production workload eventually has to answer two questions: can we survive a failure, which is high availability, and how fast can we come back, which is disaster recovery. The entire conversation reduces to two numbers, quoted per workload.

R-T-O, the Recovery Time Objective, is how long the workload can be down before the business is in real trouble. R-P-O, the Recovery Point Objective, is how much data the business can afford to lose, measured in time, back to the last successful backup or replication point.

Quote them per workload, never per company. The customer-facing checkout flow might need an R-T-O under five minutes and an R-P-O under thirty seconds. The back-office reporting warehouse might be perfectly fine with an R-T-O of twenty-four hours and an R-P-O of four hours. Every architectural choice that follows, synchronous versus asynchronous replication, multi-A-Z versus multi-region, hot standby versus cold backup, is paying for a smaller R-T-O or R-P-O.

And two costs scale as you tighten those numbers. Money, because you're buying more hardware, more replicas, and more cross-region bandwidth. And complexity, because you're adding more failover automation, more drift between primary and standby, and more things to test. So the only honest question is: how small is small enough for this workload? This module, H-A, D-R, cost, and migration, is the set of levers you pull to hit those two numbers without overpaying.
